---
// "Management & pay", Buffett's two questions about compensation, sourced. Stock
// comp (a real expense an owner bears) comes from the financials; the CEO-to-median
// pay ratio is pulled from the proxy when cleanly disclosed.
import language from "../data/language.json";
import { fmtMoney } from "../lib/fundamentals.mjs";

const { company } = Astro.props;
const $ = (v) => fmtMoney(v, company?.currency || "USD");
const L = company.lines || {};
const sbc = L.stockBasedComp;
const rev = L.revenue, oi = L.operatingIncome;
const comp = language?.companies?.[company.ticker]?.comp || null;

// Against revenue (scale) and operating profit (materiality). Not owner earnings:
// CFO adds SBC back, so it's baked into that denominator, a muddled comparison.
const pctOf = (n, d, dp = 0) => (n != null && d && d > 0 ? `${((n / d) * 100).toFixed(dp)}%` : null);
const sbcRev = sbc != null ? pctOf(sbc, rev) : null;
const sbcOI = sbc != null ? pctOf(sbc, oi) : null;

const show = (sbc != null && rev) || comp?.payRatio != null;
---

{show ? (
  <section class="comp">
    <div class="head">
      <h3 class="secTitle">Management &amp; pay</h3>
      {comp?.sourceUrl ? <a class="src" href={comp.sourceUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener">read the proxy →</a> : null}
    </div>
    <p class="intro">
      Two questions Buffett actually asks about pay: is stock compensation, a real expense, whatever the
      income statement pretends, quietly large, and is the top wildly out of line with the floor. He's no
      populist about it; he just wants pay that's rational and earned, and comp committees that aren't lapdogs.
    </p>

    <ul class="rows">
      {comp?.payRatio != null ? (
        <li>
          <div class="r"><span class="k">CEO pay ratio</span><span class="v">{comp.payRatio.toLocaleString()}:1</span></div>
          <p class="n">What the chief earns for every dollar the median employee makes{comp.fy ? `, per the ${comp.fy} proxy` : ""}. A high ratio isn't proof of anything, some businesses are genuinely top-heavy in scarce skill, but a runaway figure is where Buffett starts asking whether the board is doing its job or just keeping the chair company.</p>
        </li>
      ) : null}
      {sbc != null && rev ? (
        <li>
          <div class="r"><span class="k">Stock-based compensation</span><span class="v">{$(sbc)}</span></div>
          <p class="n">The slice of the business handed to employees in shares this year, {sbcRev} of revenue{sbcOI ? `, equal to ${sbcOI} of operating profit` : ""}. Buffett's oldest accounting fight: this is compensation, compensation is an expense, real whether or not the headline earnings admit it. And note the trap, the cash-flow statement adds SBC back, so the operating cash, and the owner earnings drawn from it, are flattered by exactly this amount; counted as the cost it is, what an owner keeps is lower.</p>
        </li>
      ) : null}
    </ul>
  </section>
) : null}

<style>
  .comp { margin: 24px 0; }
  .head { display: flex; align-items: baseline; justify-content: space-between; gap: 12px; flex-wrap: wrap; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule-strong); padding-bottom: 6px; }
  .head h2 { margin: 0; }
  .src { font-size: 12px; color: var(--accent); flex: 0 0 auto; }
  .intro { font-family: var(--serif); font-style: italic; font-size: 13.5px; color: var(--muted); margin: 10px 0 0; line-height: 1.55; max-width: 70ch; }

  .rows { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 14px 0 0; }
  .rows li { padding: 12px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule); }
  .r { display: flex; align-items: baseline; justify-content: space-between; gap: 12px; }
  .k { font-weight: 600; font-size: 16px; }
  .v { font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums; flex: 0 0 auto; }
  .n { font-size: 13px; color: var(--ink-dim); margin: 5px 0 0; line-height: 1.5; }
</style>
